  }
}

```

The key idea: every subtree is itself a tree whose root is `root.left` or `root.right`.



# Understanding TreeNode, Objects, References, and the Dot (`.`) Operator in Java

---

# 1. What is a Class?

```java
class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left;
    TreeNode right;

    TreeNode(int val) {
        this.val = val;
    }
}
```

## Explanation Box

> A class is a **blueprint/template** used to create objects.
>
> It does not store actual data.
>
> It only defines:
>
> - What data an object should contain.
> - What operations an object can perform.

Think of it as a form:

```text
TreeNode Form

Value      : ______
Left Child : ______
Right Child: ______
```

Every TreeNode object created from this class will have these fields.

---

# 2. Understanding the Fields

```java
int val;
TreeNode left;
TreeNode right;
```

## Explanation Box

Each TreeNode object contains:

| Field | Stores |
|---------|---------|
| val | Integer value |
| left | Reference to left child node |
| right | Reference to right child node |

Visual:

```text
+----------------+
| val   |   ?    |
| left  |   ?    |
| right |   ?    |
+----------------+
```

---

# 3. Understanding the Constructor

```java
TreeNode(int val) {
    this.val = val;
}
```

## Explanation Box

A constructor runs automatically when an object is created.

Example:

```java
TreeNode node = new TreeNode(10);
```

### Step 1: Allocate Memory

```text
+----------------+
| val   |   0    |
| left  | null   |
| right | null   |
+----------------+
```

---

### Step 2: Pass Constructor Parameter

```java
TreeNode(int val)
```

Receives:

```text
val = 10
```

---

### Step 3: Execute

```java
this.val = val;
```

Meaning:

```text
Object's val = Constructor Parameter
```

Equivalent to:

```java
object.val = 10;
```

Final object:

```text
+----------------+
| val   |  10    |
| left  | null   |
| right | null   |
+----------------+
```

---

# 4. What Does `this` Mean?

```java
this.val = val;
```

## Explanation Box

### Left Side

```java
this.val
```

means:

> The field named `val` inside the current object.

### Right Side

```java
val
```

means:

> Constructor parameter.

So:

```java
this.val = val;
```

becomes:

```text
Current Object's val = Parameter val
```

---

# 5. Creating a TreeNode Object

```java
TreeNode root = new TreeNode(10);
```

## Explanation Box

Variable:

```java
root
```

does NOT store the node itself.

It stores a reference (address) to the node.

Visual:

```text
root
 |
 V

+----------------+
| val   | 10     |
| left  | null   |
| right | null   |
+----------------+
```

---

# 6. Understanding the Dot (`.`) Operator

## Rule

> Dot (`.`) means:
>
> "Go inside this object and access one of its fields or methods."

---

### Example 1

```java
root.val
```

Read as:

```text
Go to object referred by root
↓
Access val field
```

Result:

```java
10
```

---

### Example 2

```java
root.left
```

Read as:

```text
Go to root object
↓
Access left field
```

Current result:

```java
null
```

because no left child exists.

---

# 7. Adding a Left Child

```java
root.left = new TreeNode(5);
```

## Explanation Box

Java creates a second object.

Memory:

```text
Object A

+----------------+
| val   | 10     |
| left  | ----+  |
| right | null   |
+----------------+
               |
               V

Object B

+----------------+
| val   | 5      |
| left  | null   |
| right | null   |
+----------------+
```

Now:

```java
root.left
```

points to Object B.

---

# 8. Why Does `root.left.val` Work?

```java
root.left.val
```

## Step-by-Step Box

### Step 1

```java
